<p>These are propositions that circulate in public debate, not quotations attributed to
particular people. A claim qualifies for this page only if it demonstrably circulates, if
the error in it is statistical rather than political, if our sources can settle it, and if
we would apply the same test to the opposite claim.</p>

{%- set restrictionist = collections.claims | countWhere("direction", "restrictionist") %}
{%- set proMigration = collections.claims | countWhere("direction", "pro-migration") %}
<p><strong>The current set corrects {{ restrictionist | inWords }} restrictionist claims and
{{ proMigration | inWords }} pro-migration ones.{% if restrictionist != proMigration %} That
is not an even split and we are not going to present it as one.{% endif %}</strong>
Restrictionist
misuses circulate more, so a set forced to fifty-fifty would misrepresent the field.</p>

<p>What is enforced automatically, before the site builds, is a floor: at least two claims in
each direction. A set that only ever corrected one side would fail the build. We previously
capped either direction at two-thirds, and removed that cap when it blocked us from adding
<a href="/common-claims/immigrants-are-a-drain-on-public-finances/">"immigrants are a drain
on the public finances"</a>, the correction a reader sympathetic to migration would most
want to see. A rule that prevents you correcting a claim is measuring the wrong thing.</p>

<p>Judge the balance by reading the corrections, not counting them. The two longest and most
pointed checks on this site both run against the pro-migration side.</p>

<ul class="claim-list">
  {%- for claim in collections.claims %}
  <li>
    <article>
      <h2><a href="{{ claim.url }}">{{ claim.data.claim }}</a></h2>
      <p>{{ claim.data.short_answer }}</p>
